{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:07:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:07:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2389"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2389"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.04,0.05,0.4,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2389"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2389"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2389"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67664"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1195"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6454"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10729"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44779"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. His mother reports that he had an upper respiratory tract infection two weeks ago which has resolved. He was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His growth parameters are at the 50th centile for weight and 75th centile for height.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no dysmorphic features. Abdominal examination reveals a non-tender firm mass in the left flank.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood: +2\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERed blood cells: 46/high power field (0-2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProtein: negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGlucose: negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENitrites: negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELeucocyte esterase: negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECrystals: negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum complement levels are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nephroblastoma","Autosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease","Neuroblastoma","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis","Hydronephrosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with the classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Enephroblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E (Wilms tumour): an asymptomatic unilateral flank mass with haematuria in a child aged 2-5 years. Nephroblastoma is the most common renal tumour in childhood. Around 25% of cases present with haematuria, while 40% have abdominal pain and 25% have hypertension. The absence of systemic symptoms and normal complement levels make other diagnoses less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal recessive polycystic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bilateral kidney enlargement and signs of renal failure including proteinuria and hypertension. There is often a history of oligohydramnios during pregnancy with resulting Potter sequence, which is not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents before age one year with systemic symptoms and an abdominal mass that crosses the midline. This patient\u0027s age and lack of systemic symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-streptococcal glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered given the recent upper respiratory tract infection, but the absence of proteinuria and normal complement levels make this unlikely. It would also not explain the abdominal mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydronephrosis\u003C/strong\u003E due to congenital anomalies would likely have been detected on antenatal ultrasound. While severe cases may present with a palpable kidney, isolated haematuria would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nephroblastoma (Wilms tumour) typically presents in children aged 2-5 years with an asymptomatic unilateral abdominal mass.","Haematuria occurs in 25% of nephroblastoma cases and may be the only urinary abnormality.","Initial imaging for suspected nephroblastoma should be ultrasound to avoid rupture during examination."],"references":["Davidoff A. Wilms Tumor. Advances in Pediatrics. 2012;59(1):247-267."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67664"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2389"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67664"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T19:37:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T19:38:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2389"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","